{
  "texts": [
    "We mitigate this concern through high human-judge agreement (𝜅 = 0.908) on a sample stratified across model performance tiers.",
    "Additionally, the judge did not rank itself as the top-performing model (ranking 4th at 65.1%), suggesting that any residual self-preference did not dominantly skew the relative rankings.The observational design identifies that model identity matters far more than scale, but cannot isolate which specific training factors drive disclosure behavior.",
    "Controlled training experiments manipulating RLHF weighting, safety fine-tuning data composition, and reasoning integration would determine which interventions produce transparent behavior and whether improvements generalize across professional domains.",
    "Such experiments would move from demonstrating that training matters to specifying how to train for transparency.Future work should pursue four directions.",
    "First, test whether context-dependent transparency patterns exist in frontier models and natural deployment settings, addressing questions about scope and generalization."
  ]
}